WEBVTT

00:12.880 --> 00:14.230
Being an adult is
80% misery.

00:14.430 --> 00:15.890
[Whimsical tune plays]

00:16.100 --> 00:17.360
I think <i>you're</i> at 80.

00:17.560 --> 00:18.700
I'm at 30.

00:18.900 --> 00:19.900
[Clinking]

00:20.100 --> 00:22.700
I do think the press
may pick up the poem,

00:22.900 --> 00:24.270
[Snickers]
once they hear it.

00:24.470 --> 00:25.640
He abandoned us.

00:25.840 --> 00:27.240
He abandoned <i>you.</i>

00:27.440 --> 00:28.710
Now, he's moving back.

00:28.910 --> 00:30.780
They want me to make a list
of people to fire.

00:30.980 --> 00:32.650
They were concerned
that you might panic,

00:32.850 --> 00:35.450
but I said, "No!
They're all adults."

00:35.650 --> 00:39.150
Railton is just a town
that can suck you in.

00:39.350 --> 00:40.840
Are you trying
to get me to leave?

00:43.770 --> 00:45.320
[ <i>"Won't You Tell Your Dreams?"</i>
by Lee Hazelwood playing]

00:45.530 --> 00:50.130
* Da, da...
da, da, da, da, da *

00:50.330 --> 00:56.150
* I've learned to do
some simple things *

00:56.750 --> 00:59.970
* Like lock the door

01:00.170 --> 01:01.910
* And shut the lights

01:02.110 --> 01:03.440
[Young Hank's parents arguing]

01:03.640 --> 01:09.480
* And pay the paperboy
on time *

01:09.680 --> 01:14.490
* And try and miss you
less each night *

01:14.690 --> 01:15.650
[parents arguing]

01:15.850 --> 01:20.990
* So please won't you
tell your dreams... *

01:21.190 --> 01:22.760
[clock chiming]

01:22.960 --> 01:27.830
* ...To leave my room alone?

01:28.030 --> 01:29.800
[clock chiming]

01:30.000 --> 01:36.180
* Please won't you
tell your dreams *

01:36.380 --> 01:41.310
* To leave my room alone?

01:41.510 --> 01:43.380
[clock chiming]

01:43.580 --> 01:49.890
* Da, da...
da, da, da, da, da *

01:50.090 --> 01:56.730
* Da, da...
da, da, da, da, da... *

01:56.930 --> 02:03.570
* Da, da...
da, da, da, da, da *

02:03.770 --> 02:08.710
* Da, da...
da, da, da, da, da... *

02:08.910 --> 02:10.830
[groans]

02:14.900 --> 02:19.570
[**]

02:39.590 --> 02:42.860
[**]

02:44.430 --> 02:48.100
[**]

02:50.070 --> 02:51.870
[phone ringing]

02:56.100 --> 02:57.520
Tom, this isn't a good time.

02:57.720 --> 02:59.010
<i>You got it!</i>

03:00.580 --> 03:02.260
What do you mean?
You said that--

03:02.460 --> 03:04.530
<i>I know,</i>
<i>but they loved you, Lil.</i>

03:04.730 --> 03:06.450
<i>They want you to start</i>
<i>as soon as you can.</i>

03:07.720 --> 03:09.300
Okay. Slow down.

03:09.500 --> 03:11.270
I didn't say I could take this.
You know that.

03:11.470 --> 03:12.270
<i>I know that,</i>

03:12.470 --> 03:13.410
<i>but this is a great school,</i>

03:13.610 --> 03:15.140
<i>and you'd love it here.</i>

03:15.340 --> 03:17.480
<i>You had all these ideas</i>
<i>about education back in school.</i>

03:17.680 --> 03:20.250
<i>We'll do them here,</i>
<i>and you know it will be funded.</i>

03:20.450 --> 03:21.280
[door opens]

03:21.480 --> 03:22.380
Okay. I have to go.

03:22.580 --> 03:23.780
<i>Talk to Hank, and then come.</i>

03:23.980 --> 03:24.880
<i>You deserve this.</i>

03:25.080 --> 03:26.790
Okay. Thank you. Bye.

03:26.990 --> 03:28.450
Hey.

03:28.650 --> 03:29.790
Hi.

03:29.990 --> 03:33.560
I was just looking at
the grandfather clock out there,

03:33.760 --> 03:34.990
in the pod.

03:35.190 --> 03:36.060
It's a nice piece.

03:36.260 --> 03:37.930
Your father's clock?

03:38.130 --> 03:41.770
The clock that I possess
on my property.

03:41.970 --> 03:43.150
When is that pod going?

03:44.650 --> 03:45.800
I'm going to keep the clock.

03:46.000 --> 03:47.220
You want it in the house?

03:48.220 --> 03:48.970
That piece is different.

03:49.170 --> 03:51.490
I always thought
of it as a friend.

03:52.800 --> 03:54.560
Oh. That's sweet.

03:56.970 --> 03:58.250
Hey, we're missing
two settings.

03:58.450 --> 04:00.290
We are not.

04:00.490 --> 04:02.150
Well, how many are we?

04:02.360 --> 04:03.660
Um...

04:03.860 --> 04:05.120
Billie, Gracie,

04:05.320 --> 04:06.290
Teddy, June,

04:06.490 --> 04:08.510
Rourke, Joanie, Emma.

04:09.980 --> 04:10.830
I'm missing someone.

04:11.030 --> 04:12.270
Finny, and us.

04:12.470 --> 04:13.930
You know, one time,

04:14.130 --> 04:16.470
we should throw a dinner party
for people we actually like.

04:16.670 --> 04:17.800
You know, change of pace.

04:18.000 --> 04:19.000
Do you remember

04:19.200 --> 04:23.210
when you accidentally made punch
with 151-proof rum,

04:23.410 --> 04:24.940
and Gracie fell asleep
under the table?

04:25.140 --> 04:26.680
That was fun.

04:26.880 --> 04:28.810
Although with the budget cuts,
I don't know.

04:29.010 --> 04:29.850
This year might be grim.

04:30.050 --> 04:31.650
Ten water glasses.

04:31.850 --> 04:35.050
You know, tonight is about
lowering expectations.

04:35.250 --> 04:37.360
That way, we might be
pleasantly surprised.

04:37.560 --> 04:39.460
That was almost optimism.

04:39.660 --> 04:40.730
No, No, no.

04:40.930 --> 04:43.300
I know what's going to happen.

04:43.500 --> 04:45.460
One of these bozos
is going to break down crying.

04:45.660 --> 04:46.820
It happens every year.

04:48.150 --> 04:49.740
And then...

04:49.940 --> 04:51.540
another bozo will reveal

04:51.740 --> 04:54.040
something embarrassing
and personal,

04:54.240 --> 04:56.040
and we're all left sitting there
staring at each other,

04:56.240 --> 04:58.480
wondering what the hell's
going on?

04:58.680 --> 04:59.880
All right.

05:00.080 --> 05:01.380
Eyes wide open.

05:01.580 --> 05:03.680
When did you check
the stew last?

05:03.880 --> 05:05.070
[doorbell rings]

05:06.030 --> 05:07.650
Okay, eight minutes early.

05:07.850 --> 05:09.250
That'll be the Washington-Chens.

05:09.460 --> 05:10.760
- Shall we?
- [phone ringing]

05:10.960 --> 05:14.730
Oh, I have to take this.
I'll just be a minute.

05:14.930 --> 05:16.510
Hey, Ash.

05:17.580 --> 05:19.700
I wonder
who does their landscaping.

05:19.900 --> 05:22.170
This is-- this is
what chair money gets you, huh?

05:22.370 --> 05:23.740
I guess so.

05:23.940 --> 05:25.020
Hey!

05:26.020 --> 05:27.510
- Hey!
- Hi. How are you?

05:27.710 --> 05:28.840
Right in there,
yeah, yeah.

05:29.040 --> 05:30.180
No, I need your help
with something.

05:30.380 --> 05:32.240
Oh. Oh. Um...

05:32.450 --> 05:33.950
Hi.

05:34.150 --> 05:36.280
[Ashley]
<i>You're coming to New York!</i>

05:36.480 --> 05:37.920
Oh, no.

05:38.120 --> 05:40.890
No. It's just an offer.
I'm not taking it.

05:41.090 --> 05:41.920
I can't. There's just--

05:42.120 --> 05:43.690
You know, there's just
too many obstacles.

05:43.890 --> 05:46.630
<i>Oh. But you want to, right?</i>

05:46.830 --> 05:48.290
I mean...

05:48.490 --> 05:49.600
if there was
no other considerations,

05:49.800 --> 05:51.430
then of course I want to.

05:51.630 --> 05:53.930
<i>Oh. Hmm. Is Hank mad</i>
<i>about what happened?</i>

05:54.130 --> 05:55.730
Nothing happened.

05:55.930 --> 05:57.070
<i>Oh, you didn't tell him.</i>

05:57.270 --> 05:58.770
Nothing happened.

05:58.970 --> 06:00.070
<i>Well, look, no, right.</i>

06:00.270 --> 06:01.440
<i>I wouldn't have told</i>
<i>my husband either.</i>

06:01.640 --> 06:02.580
Come on.

06:02.780 --> 06:04.280
Look, he surprised me.

06:04.480 --> 06:06.080
I was on the phone,
I wasn't even paying attention.

06:06.280 --> 06:07.750
It was nothing.

06:07.950 --> 06:10.920
It looks heavy.

06:11.120 --> 06:12.870
You can't see weight.

06:14.700 --> 06:15.790
What if we drop it?

06:15.990 --> 06:19.140
Don't let go with your hands,
and we won't drop it.

06:20.940 --> 06:22.060
No! No! Put it down!
Put it down!

06:22.260 --> 06:23.800
Put it down. Put it down!

06:24.000 --> 06:26.330
What happened?

06:26.530 --> 06:28.000
I panicked.

06:28.200 --> 06:29.840
I can't leave it out here.
It's going to rain.

06:30.040 --> 06:31.000
Yeah. Sorry, Hank.

06:31.200 --> 06:32.840
My brass band plays Sunday,

06:33.040 --> 06:34.310
and, you know, the French horn,

06:34.510 --> 06:36.580
it's much more
latissimus-centric

06:36.780 --> 06:38.110
than most people think.

06:38.310 --> 06:39.980
I can't risk a strain.

06:40.180 --> 06:42.250
<i>Oh, Lil. I can't wait</i>
<i>for your ass to get here.</i>

06:42.450 --> 06:44.480
<i>I mean, I'm not as eager</i>
<i>as Tom or anything.</i>

06:44.680 --> 06:46.820
<i>I mean, that guy's,</i>
<i>like, drooling for you.</i>

06:47.020 --> 06:48.790
- Okay, stop it.
- [door closes]

06:48.990 --> 06:49.940
Okay, I gotta go.

06:55.140 --> 06:55.990
Make yourself something. I--

06:56.190 --> 06:57.000
- Was it Teddy and June?
- Yeah.

06:57.200 --> 06:59.130
Are you okay?

06:59.330 --> 07:00.680
I got the job.
The Arlyle job.

07:01.950 --> 07:03.800
You did?
That's amazing!

07:04.000 --> 07:06.470
I mean, of course you did.

07:06.670 --> 07:07.870
You're amazing.

07:08.070 --> 07:09.840
- I'm so proud of you.
- Thank you.

07:10.040 --> 07:10.840
I really didn't
expect to get it.

07:11.040 --> 07:12.680
Is it a good offer?

07:12.880 --> 07:14.010
Did you talk specifics?

07:14.210 --> 07:15.110
- We didn't get into it.
- Yeah.

07:15.310 --> 07:16.180
It's an offer.

07:16.380 --> 07:17.530
Fantastic news.

07:20.300 --> 07:21.690
Oh...

07:21.890 --> 07:23.020
talk about leverage, right?

07:23.220 --> 07:24.960
You are going to bring
East Railton High to its knees.

07:25.160 --> 07:26.490
You're going to get
so many cleaning supplies,

07:26.690 --> 07:28.030
they're going to give you
your own closet.

07:28.230 --> 07:29.190
Right?

07:29.390 --> 07:30.630
Yeah, totally.

07:30.830 --> 07:32.150
I'm going to be
queen of that place.

07:40.320 --> 07:44.710
[**]

07:44.910 --> 07:45.530
Hello.

07:45.790 --> 07:46.980
Hey.

07:47.180 --> 07:48.580
- Welcome.
- Thank you.

07:48.780 --> 07:49.580
Uh, Lily?

07:49.780 --> 07:50.850
She's right
in the kitchen. Yeah.

07:51.050 --> 07:52.300
Okay. Thanks.

07:54.340 --> 07:55.720
Now, before you come in,

07:55.920 --> 07:57.510
could you help me
with something?

07:58.740 --> 08:00.480
Just that.

08:01.480 --> 08:05.150
Oh! Oh! Would you like me
to also bust up a chifforobe?

08:07.750 --> 08:09.420
I'm not your moving company.

08:20.230 --> 08:22.110
[ <i>"Y Sin Embargo Tú Estabas Ahí"</i>
by Pippo Spera playing]

08:22.310 --> 08:25.380
[Hank, thinking] <i>Why do people</i>
<i>my age have parties?</i>

08:25.580 --> 08:26.950
<i>I mean, I get it</i>
<i>when you're in your 20s,</i>

08:27.150 --> 08:28.690
<i>and it's all about getting laid,</i>

08:28.890 --> 08:30.460
<i>but what's in it for us?</i>

08:30.660 --> 08:33.130
<i>I think it's the same reason</i>
<i>people gamble.</i>

08:33.330 --> 08:34.790
<i>The thrill of possibility.</i>

08:34.990 --> 08:35.930
<i>The roll of the die.</i>

08:36.130 --> 08:36.930
<i>Right before the party,</i>

08:37.130 --> 08:38.030
<i>where you think, "What if?</i>

08:38.230 --> 08:41.200
<i>What if I have</i>
<i>a good conversation?</i>

08:41.400 --> 08:43.770
<i>What if</i>
<i>a real friendship emerges?</i>

08:43.970 --> 08:46.070
<i>What if Penelope Cruz's car</i>
<i>breaks down outside</i>

08:46.270 --> 08:48.110
<i>and she needs</i>
<i>to stay for dinner?"</i>

08:48.310 --> 08:49.780
<i>But then the party starts.</i>

08:49.980 --> 08:52.980
<i>The die is cast,</i>
<i>and everybody is a loser.</i>

08:53.180 --> 08:56.110
[in French]
* ...Par la fenêtre ouverte *

08:56.310 --> 08:58.720
* Posait
sur ton corps dénudé... *

08:58.920 --> 09:00.950
Why don't we have
a view of the lake?

09:01.150 --> 09:01.990
Paul.

09:02.190 --> 09:03.720
- Not again.
- What?

09:03.920 --> 09:04.910
I shouldn't have this?

09:06.140 --> 09:07.290
It's not the Mediterranean.

09:07.490 --> 09:08.960
It's a modest lake
in Pennsylvania.

09:09.160 --> 09:10.480
I can't have a view of it?

09:11.980 --> 09:14.170
Well, I'm very happy
where we live.

09:14.370 --> 09:17.300
All right,
but you'd be happier here.

09:17.500 --> 09:19.140
Hmm?

09:19.340 --> 09:21.440
Right?

09:21.640 --> 09:22.440
See?

09:22.640 --> 09:23.810
This is some bullshit.

09:24.010 --> 09:25.140
This place should be mine.

09:25.340 --> 09:27.180
Did I tell you I outbid him
by ten grand?

09:27.380 --> 09:28.850
Yeah, like a hundred times.

09:29.050 --> 09:29.820
And you also told me

09:30.020 --> 09:31.080
how you showed up here
with a builder

09:31.280 --> 09:32.620
and told that old man
that was selling the place

09:32.820 --> 09:34.840
that you were going
to tear down his childhood home.

09:36.300 --> 09:38.840
Yeah, well,
this place was a dump.

09:40.510 --> 09:41.910
Still is.

09:43.150 --> 09:45.260
You know, I bet Hank
doesn't even know what he has.

09:45.460 --> 09:46.530
But if it was mine,

09:46.730 --> 09:49.920
I would clear this path
so you could get to the lake.

09:52.190 --> 09:53.790
Build my deck out.

09:57.160 --> 09:58.040
Lily.

09:58.240 --> 09:59.040
Oh, hi.

09:59.240 --> 10:00.110
It's been so long.

10:00.310 --> 10:01.180
- I know.
- Thanks for doing this.

10:01.380 --> 10:02.720
Thank you for being here.

10:02.920 --> 10:03.920
This is fun.

10:04.120 --> 10:07.390
Hank mentioned you, uh,
had an interview at Arlyle.

10:07.590 --> 10:08.820
He did?

10:09.020 --> 10:10.290
Oh, I forget
he talks about me sometimes.

10:10.490 --> 10:12.020
I know that school.

10:12.220 --> 10:13.860
They're a huge
a cappella feeder.

10:14.060 --> 10:15.380
Five of the 14 Whiffenpoofs.

10:16.510 --> 10:17.360
Oh, I didn't know.

10:17.560 --> 10:18.460
Yeah.

10:18.660 --> 10:19.830
So?

10:20.030 --> 10:20.900
How'd it go?

10:21.100 --> 10:21.970
It went very well.

10:22.170 --> 10:25.240
Um, I have an offer, actually.

10:25.440 --> 10:26.370
Um, but, you know,

10:26.570 --> 10:27.970
it's very complicated
right now, so.

10:28.170 --> 10:30.040
But you're taking it,
though, right?

10:30.240 --> 10:31.540
No.

10:31.740 --> 10:33.000
Are you crazy?

10:35.660 --> 10:37.050
I mean, um...

10:37.250 --> 10:38.570
why not?

10:39.740 --> 10:41.740
Well, I can't take a job
in New York right now.

10:43.040 --> 10:44.220
Oh...

10:44.420 --> 10:45.410
That's too bad.

10:46.910 --> 10:48.910
Well, congratulations anyway.

10:50.410 --> 10:52.060
Thanks.

10:52.260 --> 10:53.320
Excuse me.

10:56.080 --> 10:57.100
[Emma] So if I taste it,

10:57.300 --> 10:58.570
it's not like a stroke,
it's actually in there.

10:58.770 --> 11:00.910
Yeah, it's not artificial rust,
it's real.

11:01.110 --> 11:02.170
[Teddy] Oh, okay.

11:02.370 --> 11:03.210
Real prepared rust.

11:03.410 --> 11:04.340
Great. Perfect.

11:04.540 --> 11:05.340
[Teddy] Okay.

11:05.540 --> 11:07.180
Yeah, and it is just...

11:07.380 --> 11:08.180
Oh, we're still
talking about this.

11:08.380 --> 11:09.210
...such a magnificent animal.

11:09.410 --> 11:11.550
I actually like going

11:11.750 --> 11:13.750
to the school plays
of my friends' children.

11:13.950 --> 11:14.890
That's gross.

11:15.090 --> 11:16.760
No. The bottomless need
for attention,

11:16.960 --> 11:18.590
it's not yet ugly,

11:18.790 --> 11:19.890
unlike adult actors.

11:20.090 --> 11:21.530
Doesn't a bottomless
need for attention

11:21.730 --> 11:23.100
make you feel at home?

11:23.300 --> 11:25.060
Why would I think that tonight
would be any different?

11:25.260 --> 11:26.400
I don't know.

11:26.600 --> 11:27.870
You can take the asshole
out of the English department,

11:28.070 --> 11:29.070
but you can't take--

11:29.270 --> 11:30.270
No. It's not going
to make sense.

11:30.470 --> 11:31.440
Hold on.

11:31.640 --> 11:32.770
You can't take
the English department out of--

11:32.970 --> 11:33.740
Nope.

11:33.940 --> 11:36.110
They can trace
its lineage back to 1882.

11:36.310 --> 11:37.140
Whoa.

11:37.340 --> 11:38.410
I can't do that
with my own family.

11:38.610 --> 11:39.810
Well, they hate you, so.

11:40.010 --> 11:41.280
No. Now, if June
doesn't give me a baby

11:41.480 --> 11:42.280
by next year,

11:42.480 --> 11:43.320
I'm getting two.

11:43.520 --> 11:44.450
That's not how babies work.

11:44.650 --> 11:46.990
I'm throwing away
her stupid, little cat-dogs.

11:47.190 --> 11:48.290
Oh, okay.

11:48.490 --> 11:50.460
You won't believe
what I just heard.

11:50.660 --> 11:52.830
Lily got a job offer
at the Arlyle School,

11:53.030 --> 11:53.990
and she's not taking it.

11:54.190 --> 11:56.160
- You mean she's taking it.
- Right?

11:56.360 --> 11:57.260
I mean, she has to take it.

11:57.460 --> 11:59.300
[clears throat]

11:59.500 --> 12:00.670
You know,

12:00.870 --> 12:03.940
if the university really wanted
to help with department morale,

12:04.140 --> 12:06.100
they'd give us a stipend
to keep us apart.

12:06.300 --> 12:07.410
[Lily chuckles]

12:07.610 --> 12:10.240
Well, maybe
we should take the job.

12:10.440 --> 12:12.180
We'd have a whole new set
of circumstances

12:12.380 --> 12:13.680
to complain about.

12:13.880 --> 12:14.750
Yeah, that's true.

12:14.950 --> 12:16.830
And there's New York, of course.

12:18.330 --> 12:19.730
You're not serious, are you?

12:20.840 --> 12:21.750
Maybe I am.

12:21.950 --> 12:24.160
Yeah, but we already
talked about this.

12:24.360 --> 12:25.520
Only in theory.

12:25.720 --> 12:26.490
There was no offer before, so.

12:26.690 --> 12:27.690
It's real now.

12:27.890 --> 12:29.130
- [Gracie] You heard about that.
- [Billie] Shenanigan.

12:29.330 --> 12:30.800
Yeah. All right.

12:31.000 --> 12:32.930
Well, um...

12:33.130 --> 12:34.170
maybe we should have
this conversation

12:34.370 --> 12:35.670
when we're hosting
a bigger event,

12:35.870 --> 12:37.170
like a wedding, or a parade.

12:37.370 --> 12:38.540
[Lily chuckles]

12:38.740 --> 12:40.290
Okay. You're right.
We'll talk about it later.

12:41.790 --> 12:44.230
Well, sure,

12:54.000 --> 12:56.970
[**]

12:59.570 --> 13:00.940
Oh, hey, guys.

13:02.880 --> 13:04.360
Hi. Yeah.

13:04.560 --> 13:06.060
Ah.

13:06.260 --> 13:07.900
