26:28.870 --> 26:31.340
how proud I am of my wife.

26:31.540 --> 26:34.210
Lily got
an amazing job opportunity

26:34.410 --> 26:36.510
at a very respected school
in New York.

26:36.710 --> 26:38.840
Many of you already know.

26:39.040 --> 26:40.280
It's wonderful,

26:40.480 --> 26:43.510
and I just wanted to, uh,
show her my appreciation.

26:43.720 --> 26:44.620
To Lily.

26:44.820 --> 26:45.720
- To Lily!
- To Lily!

26:45.920 --> 26:47.640
Thank you.
I appreciate that.

26:48.800 --> 26:50.390
It's something
I'm very excited about, so.

26:50.590 --> 26:51.890
- As well you should be.
- So, what about the house, then?

26:52.090 --> 26:52.890
It's an incredible--

26:53.090 --> 26:54.990
[Billie] Wait a second.
Wait a second.

26:55.190 --> 26:57.810
Like, she got the job,
and he's going?

26:59.010 --> 27:00.130
Spanky's going to New York?

27:00.330 --> 27:01.230
[Hank] It's not your concern.

27:01.430 --> 27:05.540
Well, it does affect us
quite a bit.

27:05.740 --> 27:06.700
- Does it?
- How so?

27:06.900 --> 27:08.240
You know exactly how so,
you twits.

27:08.440 --> 27:11.180
Well, we haven't made
a decision,

27:11.380 --> 27:12.880
so it's not going
to affect you tonight.

27:13.080 --> 27:15.650
[Gracie] Oh, come on, Hank.
You have to go.

27:15.850 --> 27:19.350
A path has opened up for Lily.

27:19.550 --> 27:20.720
It's just...

27:20.920 --> 27:22.320
It happened for a reason.

27:22.520 --> 27:23.590
[Billie] How can they take it?

27:23.790 --> 27:25.220
Hank's qualified for nothing.

27:25.420 --> 27:27.060
What's he gonna do?

27:27.260 --> 27:28.490
Play sax in the subway?

27:28.690 --> 27:30.230
[laughing]

27:30.430 --> 27:31.230
Thank you, Billie.

27:31.430 --> 27:32.600
[Rourke] He's a writer.

27:32.800 --> 27:34.830
He can go to one of those
stupid coffee shops

27:35.030 --> 27:37.400
and be one of those cliches,
you know.

27:37.600 --> 27:38.540
He'd love that.

27:38.740 --> 27:39.740
That sounds nice.

27:39.940 --> 27:40.740
Yeah, it does sound nice.

27:40.940 --> 27:41.770
No, actually.

27:41.970 --> 27:43.570
Well, the poem that I wrote,

27:43.780 --> 27:45.580
the one that's coming out
in <i>The Atlantic</i> ?

27:45.780 --> 27:48.080
"The Seven Sisters of Tobias".

27:48.280 --> 27:50.050
I wrote that in the city.

27:50.250 --> 27:52.180
I'm just--
I'm so stimulated there.

27:52.380 --> 27:54.250
You can take a walk
on the High Line,

27:54.450 --> 27:56.750
or just stroll
through the Village

27:56.950 --> 27:59.560
with the ghost
of Allen Ginsberg.

27:59.760 --> 28:00.610
Have you ever been to New York?

28:02.710 --> 28:05.200
Hank, if you were to leave
in the middle of term,

28:05.400 --> 28:08.430
would the Chair just go
to the next person in rotation,

28:08.630 --> 28:10.130
or would we have to take a vote?

28:10.330 --> 28:12.390
- That's a great question. Yeah.
- How would that work?

28:14.220 --> 28:16.310
How's everyone liking
the stew tonight?

28:16.510 --> 28:18.140
I ground my own paprika.

28:18.340 --> 28:19.980
Oh, it's very good.
Yeah, delicious.

28:20.180 --> 28:20.980
That's good. Yeah.

28:21.180 --> 28:22.060
It tastes the same.

28:22.900 --> 28:24.030
[door opening]

28:26.030 --> 28:26.820
Hi, everyone.

28:27.020 --> 28:28.550
- Hey.
- Oh, hey.

28:28.750 --> 28:29.550
Hi, Julie.

28:29.750 --> 28:31.990
Um, can I talk to you?

28:32.190 --> 28:33.260
Now? Like, right now?

28:33.460 --> 28:34.630
Yeah.

28:34.830 --> 28:36.080
Okay.

28:41.620 --> 28:42.470
[door closes]

28:42.670 --> 28:43.470
- Do you want more?
- Yes, please.

28:43.670 --> 28:45.140
Anybody want a refresher?

28:45.340 --> 28:46.840
- Yes.
- Yeah.

28:47.040 --> 28:48.140
[Hank] No.

28:48.340 --> 28:49.470
Okay, so, um, how are we--

28:49.670 --> 28:50.740
how are we doing?

28:50.940 --> 28:52.930
How we doin', you know?
How are we doing?

28:57.970 --> 28:59.100
[indistinct conversation]

29:00.470 --> 29:03.490
Uh, do you guys, like, after,
do you talk about it?

29:03.690 --> 29:06.690
Like, what was touched
and untouched?

29:06.890 --> 29:08.460
I would cool it down a bit.

29:08.660 --> 29:11.500
Teddy doesn't like
desperate men for me.

29:11.700 --> 29:12.930
Jesus. Desperate?

29:13.130 --> 29:14.170
[Gracie] Hank.

29:14.370 --> 29:15.370
Hank?

29:15.570 --> 29:18.500
I think we need an answer
to June's question.

29:18.700 --> 29:19.670
It's only fair.

29:19.870 --> 29:21.370
[sighs]

29:21.570 --> 29:22.960
Ask Emma.

29:25.830 --> 29:28.950
What? Why am I the only one
who has read the bylaws?

29:29.150 --> 29:30.550
It's, like, three pages.

29:30.750 --> 29:32.880
No. You know what?
I'm not telling you.

29:33.080 --> 29:35.150
[June] Emma, please.
We need to know.

29:35.350 --> 29:37.960
[Gracie] Emma, those are
a very difficult three pages.

29:38.160 --> 29:39.290
It's very dry stuff.

29:39.490 --> 29:41.360
Oh, god.
All right. Fine.

29:41.560 --> 29:43.660
If the chair
needs to leave his position

29:43.860 --> 29:45.560
due to force majeure,

29:45.760 --> 29:48.830
the position goes into rotation
and no vote is needed.

29:49.030 --> 29:51.000
- Force majeure?
- Mm-hmm.

29:51.200 --> 29:52.070
Oh.

29:52.270 --> 29:55.210
Since when is moving to New York
an act of God?

29:55.410 --> 29:56.340
[Teddy]
A job at the Arlyle School

29:56.540 --> 29:58.210
is an act of God.

29:58.410 --> 30:00.040
Do you know five of
the 14 Whiffenpoofs went there?

30:00.240 --> 30:01.330
That's a lot of Whiffenpoofs.

30:02.460 --> 30:04.150
* Whiffenpoofs...

30:04.350 --> 30:06.080
- * Whiffenpoo--
- * Whiffenpoo--

30:06.280 --> 30:07.520
* Whiffenpoofs...

30:07.720 --> 30:08.550
You're all doing my note.

30:08.750 --> 30:10.150
[all harmonizing]

30:10.350 --> 30:12.360
Please stop doing this...

30:12.560 --> 30:14.990
Please stop doing this.

30:15.190 --> 30:17.410
Where in New York
do you think you'd want to live?

30:19.180 --> 30:22.030
Well, actually,
I've thought about this.

30:22.230 --> 30:23.370
We love Brooklyn,

30:23.570 --> 30:25.600
particularly Greenpoint
and Williamsburg.

30:25.800 --> 30:27.070
- Oh, yes.
- Right?

30:27.270 --> 30:28.340
Um, of course,

30:28.540 --> 30:30.070
my commute would be much better
from the Upper West Side,

30:30.270 --> 30:33.080
but we'd probably
never be able to afford that.

30:33.280 --> 30:35.950
Well, you could if you...

30:36.150 --> 30:37.110
* ...Sell me your place!

30:37.310 --> 30:38.750
* You could
sell me your place! *

30:38.950 --> 30:40.080
* Come on
and sell me your place! *

30:40.280 --> 30:41.450
I hate it
when you get like this.

30:41.650 --> 30:42.550
Listen.

30:42.750 --> 30:43.450
Selling you this place

30:43.650 --> 30:45.420
would barely cover
the downpayment

30:45.620 --> 30:46.590
on a place in New York.

30:46.790 --> 30:48.430
[Lily] They did mention
a moving stipend,

30:48.630 --> 30:49.690
but you're right, Paul.

30:49.890 --> 30:50.760
We could use some extra money.

30:50.960 --> 30:53.970
And, um, the good news is

30:54.170 --> 30:55.970
that we also own the plot
right next to ours.

30:56.170 --> 30:57.230
Also not for sale.

30:57.430 --> 30:59.440
[Lily] I'd be very interested
in an offer, Paul.

30:59.640 --> 31:00.470
[Rourke]
Is it a large plot?

31:00.670 --> 31:02.240
Is it larger than this one?

31:02.440 --> 31:04.440
For God's sake.
What is wrong with you?

31:04.640 --> 31:06.390
Can you ever be happy
with what is?

31:24.610 --> 31:25.730
She'll cool off.

31:25.930 --> 31:26.830
Hey, Hank.

31:27.030 --> 31:28.230
I'll give you 10%
over market value.

31:28.430 --> 31:30.570
[Hank] It's not for sale
any time soon.

31:30.770 --> 31:32.100
Well, I just had

31:32.300 --> 31:34.010
a very interesting conversation
with our daughter,

31:34.210 --> 31:36.440
and she says that, um,
she's coming with me.

31:36.640 --> 31:37.910
[Gracie] Oh!

31:38.110 --> 31:40.140
She and her husband
have flexible work situations.

31:40.340 --> 31:41.110
Oh, that's nice.

31:41.310 --> 31:42.510
And she mentioned
that you, Hank,

31:42.710 --> 31:43.810
recently suggested

31:44.020 --> 31:45.980
that she move to a city
with more opportunities.

31:46.180 --> 31:47.150
Oh, there you go.

31:47.350 --> 31:49.520
I guess we're going to need
a bigger place.

31:49.720 --> 31:52.860
[Rourke] Well, this sounds like
good news all around.

31:53.060 --> 31:54.190
Win-win-win.

31:54.390 --> 31:55.630
No, no, no.

31:55.830 --> 31:56.960
Look. Look.

31:57.160 --> 31:58.760
We're not making a decision
right here,

31:58.960 --> 31:59.830
not with this group.

32:00.030 --> 32:01.170
So let's go back

32:01.370 --> 32:03.670
to our usual
awful, awkward conversation

32:03.870 --> 32:05.000
that we're all so good at.

32:05.200 --> 32:06.000
[laughing]

32:06.200 --> 32:07.040
All right?

32:07.240 --> 32:08.590
Because nothing is happening.

32:12.160 --> 32:13.460
But something is happening.

32:14.500 --> 32:16.950
Well, nothing's happening
right now.

32:17.150 --> 32:18.600
Julie just happened right now.

32:20.000 --> 32:23.020
It appears that the situation
is evolving in real time.

32:23.220 --> 32:24.060
Julie isn't going anywhere.

32:24.260 --> 32:25.470
That's not up to you, is it?

32:27.470 --> 32:28.990
I'm not going.

32:29.190 --> 32:30.140
I'm...

32:32.980 --> 32:36.030
...going to stay here,

32:36.230 --> 32:38.370
even if you go.

32:38.570 --> 32:39.400
Okay?

32:39.600 --> 32:41.790
So how's that
for a decision made right now?

32:57.870 --> 33:00.890
Hank, you know what,
I think I can taste the paprika.

33:01.090 --> 33:02.060
It's much fresher.

33:02.260 --> 33:04.400
- Yeah, it's a fresher taste.
- Yeah.

33:04.600 --> 33:05.600
Hits you more, yeah.

33:05.800 --> 33:07.930
- Let's play a game.
- Oh, yes!

33:08.130 --> 33:09.200
That's a great idea!

33:09.400 --> 33:12.740
Do you remember how we used
to all play Celebrity?

33:12.940 --> 33:14.070
I'll certainly never forget

33:14.270 --> 33:16.440
the time that Paul didn't know
who Andrea Dworkin was.

33:16.640 --> 33:17.910
[laughing]

33:18.110 --> 33:20.240
Lily, where do you keep
the pencils and the paper?

33:20.440 --> 33:22.710
No. This game is called
"Percentage Of Happiness".

33:22.910 --> 33:24.620
[Gracie] Oh!

33:24.820 --> 33:25.850
Goodness.

33:26.050 --> 33:27.720
I do not think
that I know that game.

33:27.920 --> 33:29.790
I think I played
that game once.

33:29.990 --> 33:31.890
I was at a book reading
with Johnny Franzen--

33:32.090 --> 33:33.360
It's a really simple game.

33:33.560 --> 33:35.960
So, how you play is
you answer this question--

33:36.160 --> 33:38.900
"What percentage
of happiness am I?"

33:39.100 --> 33:39.960
[Gracie] Oh.

33:40.160 --> 33:43.300
And, "What percentage
of happiness is so low

33:43.500 --> 33:45.140
that you should be willing
to make a change?"

33:45.340 --> 33:46.200
[Gracie] Oh.

33:46.400 --> 33:47.540
We'll just go around the room.

33:47.740 --> 33:48.940
Gracie, do you want
to kick us off?

33:49.140 --> 33:51.380
Oh. Um, yes. Okay.

33:51.580 --> 33:53.610
Um, well, um,

33:53.810 --> 33:55.310
as you know,
I'm having a very good day,

33:55.510 --> 33:57.550
so I think I would, um--

33:57.750 --> 34:03.290
Oh, I-- I would put myself
at, um, oh...

34:03.490 --> 34:05.290
95% happiness!

34:05.490 --> 34:06.420
Wow.

34:06.620 --> 34:07.660
And when would I make a change?

34:07.860 --> 34:09.930
Um, oh, I don't know.

34:10.130 --> 34:10.930
Um--

34:11.130 --> 34:11.930
Would you just--

34:12.130 --> 34:13.060
60%!

34:13.260 --> 34:14.470
Yeah, 60%.

34:14.670 --> 34:15.330
60%.

34:15.530 --> 34:17.170
All right.
I would, uh--

34:17.370 --> 34:19.090
[Lily] That's very interesting.
What about you, Hank?

34:20.120 --> 34:21.310
Oh, wait.
Actually, I already know

34:21.510 --> 34:22.770
the answer
to the first question.

34:22.970 --> 34:24.910
You told me a while ago.

34:25.110 --> 34:26.180
I believe it was 20.

34:26.380 --> 34:28.810
You are 20% happy.

34:29.010 --> 34:30.810
Oh.

34:31.010 --> 34:33.150
That does sound
pretty low, Spanky.

34:33.350 --> 34:36.250
- No, that's high for him.
- That does sound like Hank.

34:36.450 --> 34:37.390
[Lily] So question number two--

34:37.590 --> 34:40.160
what percentage
would you have to drop down to

34:40.360 --> 34:41.380
in order to make a change?

34:43.280 --> 34:44.330
10?

34:44.530 --> 34:45.660
Or...

34:45.860 --> 34:47.050
zero?

34:57.560 --> 35:01.400
[**]

35:06.470 --> 35:08.270
[indistinct party conversation]

35:14.010 --> 35:15.980
A little wine, hey?

35:17.640 --> 35:18.550
Or no?

35:21.520 --> 35:22.050
You know, guys.

35:22.720 --> 35:24.740
I've been thinking about it,

35:24.940 --> 35:26.470
and I think this just isn't me.

35:26.670 --> 35:28.410
For no real reason.

35:28.610 --> 35:30.570
It was fun imagining
what might be,

35:30.770 --> 35:33.340
but I'm going to have to
respectfully bow out.

35:33.540 --> 35:37.300
Oh. Are you sure?

35:39.300 --> 35:40.300
Oh, come on.

35:45.070 --> 35:49.180
[**]

35:53.880 --> 35:56.600
Honey...

35:56.800 --> 36:00.000
sorry I brought Julie into this.

36:00.200 --> 36:01.490
It was childish of me.

36:02.690 --> 36:03.740
I didn't handle it well.

36:03.940 --> 36:05.860
No, you didn't.

36:08.360 --> 36:10.610
You take that great job,

36:10.810 --> 36:13.220
and I'll keep my shitty job.

36:13.420 --> 36:14.750
You come out here when you can,

36:14.950 --> 36:17.920
and I'll go into the city,

36:18.120 --> 36:19.370
make it work.

36:24.780 --> 36:29.550
[**]

36:31.120 --> 36:35.120
"Marriage is sweeter,
sweeter than you think, think."

36:37.360 --> 36:39.210
- [Gracie] Anne Waldman.
- [Finny] Indeed.

36:39.410 --> 36:40.480
- "Stereo".
- Mm-hmm.

36:40.680 --> 36:42.230
Very nice.

36:43.130 --> 36:44.780
You know, there was
a period of time

36:44.980 --> 36:46.950
where Teddy and I
were long distance,

36:47.150 --> 36:48.120
and it actually
strengthened our marriage.

36:48.320 --> 36:49.150
Yeah.

36:49.350 --> 36:50.570
That's nice to hear.

36:51.810 --> 36:53.220
We developed
a different foundation

36:53.420 --> 36:56.160
for our own unique relationship,

36:56.360 --> 36:58.810
and it made us
closer than before.

36:59.780 --> 37:00.930
[Teddy]
Best decision we ever made.

37:01.130 --> 37:02.130
[June] Best decision.

37:02.330 --> 37:04.400
I mean, there are days
I want to punch him in the face.

37:04.600 --> 37:05.400
Don't get me wrong.

37:05.600 --> 37:06.600
[laughing]

37:06.800 --> 37:08.170
When I go on about my research.

37:08.370 --> 37:09.970
Funny story.

37:10.170 --> 37:11.310
You want to hear a story?

37:11.510 --> 37:12.780
I have the best

37:12.980 --> 37:15.310
long-distance relationship
story ever.

37:15.510 --> 37:16.350
And don't worry.

37:16.550 --> 37:17.410
It's not about me
wanting your house.

37:17.610 --> 37:19.020
[laughing]

37:19.220 --> 37:22.350
I've mentioned
my first wife, Barbara, right?

37:22.550 --> 37:24.090
Uh, God rest her soul.

37:24.290 --> 37:26.820
Well, she and I met in college,

37:27.020 --> 37:28.460
freshman year,

37:28.660 --> 37:32.260
and it was just supposed to be
one of those hook-ups.

37:32.460 --> 37:34.110
Damn, she was fine.

37:36.620 --> 37:38.340
Yeah. We went to her room
that first night,

37:38.540 --> 37:40.600
and guess what?

37:40.800 --> 37:43.170
I never left.

37:43.370 --> 37:48.380
I, uh, spent my freshman year
sharing a single bed with her.

37:48.580 --> 37:50.110
She was the one
who introduced me to poetry.

37:50.310 --> 37:51.520
Oh.

37:51.720 --> 37:54.700
We would, uh,
recite Blake to each other.

37:56.500 --> 38:00.660
We never spent one night apart
for all four years of college,

38:00.860 --> 38:02.640
and we got married right after.

38:03.640 --> 38:05.810
Had a destination wedding
like a couple of jerks.

38:06.980 --> 38:08.280
Tuscany, for God's sakes.

38:10.050 --> 38:13.990
Well, we didn't get into
the same Ph.D. program, though.

38:15.660 --> 38:16.740
The closest
we could get to each other

38:16.940 --> 38:20.240
was a 12-hour drive.

38:20.440 --> 38:22.400
I went to Chapel Hill
and she went to Chicago.

38:23.660 --> 38:27.720
And I just remember
missing her so much

38:27.920 --> 38:31.170
that I decided to go visit her
that first weekend.

38:32.970 --> 38:34.220
I didn't have a car,

38:34.430 --> 38:36.530
so I decided
to put up some flyers

38:36.730 --> 38:37.590
to get a ride,

38:37.790 --> 38:38.900
and I got one from this woman

38:39.100 --> 38:42.400
who was visiting
this guy down there,

38:42.600 --> 38:48.000
and we talk in the car...

38:48.200 --> 38:51.440
and it is...

38:51.640 --> 38:56.830
the most interesting,
brilliant ride of my life.

38:59.270 --> 39:00.770
Everything she says.

39:01.900 --> 39:05.590
She made the trip feel like
a hot-air balloon ride.

39:05.790 --> 39:08.510
[Gracie] Ooh.

39:11.710 --> 39:15.870
I thought I knew what love was,

39:16.070 --> 39:17.700
but I was just learning.

39:17.900 --> 39:20.570
I thought I had found my person,

39:20.770 --> 39:22.860
but I was fooling myself.

39:25.690 --> 39:28.040
She dropped me off at Barbara's.

39:28.240 --> 39:28.950
I took one look at her,

39:29.150 --> 39:31.250
and I...

39:31.450 --> 39:32.730
I asked for a divorce.

39:34.870 --> 39:40.320
Now that I knew
what love really felt like...

39:40.520 --> 39:42.210
I had to.

39:44.650 --> 39:46.460
I went back outside.

39:46.660 --> 39:50.400
I didn't know
how I was going to find her,

39:50.600 --> 39:54.760
but guess who was still there
in the car, waiting.

40:01.500 --> 40:03.180
- Yes!
- Come on.

40:03.380 --> 40:05.750
We've been together ever since.

40:05.950 --> 40:07.820
Yes.

40:08.020 --> 40:09.270
Quite a story.

40:10.970 --> 40:12.070
That's a divorce story.

40:14.170 --> 40:15.360
[Billie]
You should go with her, Spanky.

40:15.560 --> 40:17.330
Before she finds her Joanie.

40:17.530 --> 40:19.780
I already found my Joanie.

40:21.580 --> 40:23.020
You never really know
about people.

40:24.490 --> 40:25.500
No.

40:25.700 --> 40:27.300
I know my wife.

40:27.500 --> 40:28.710
I know Lily.

40:28.910 --> 40:30.010
We don't have secrets.

40:30.210 --> 40:33.090
We tell each other everything
right away.

40:35.430 --> 40:36.810
That's right. We do.

40:37.010 --> 40:38.630
Where does Tom live again?

40:39.770 --> 40:41.450
Mm.

40:41.650 --> 40:42.700
I think he lives in Greenpoint.

40:43.770 --> 40:45.120
Who's Tom?

